default5.1.
default 
defaultThere are a number of factors that limit community transport from playing a wider role in delivering transport services.  The limitations do not include enthusiasm and a willingness to deliver.  
default&#xa0;
default5.2.
default 
defaultThere is a limit to what volunteers ca
defaultn be expected to do.  Most volunteers do not want to work early in the morning, late in the evening or at weekends.  This limits the services that can be offered by volunteer dependent operators.
default&#xa0;
default5.3.
default 
defaultCTOs
default tend to work in very specific areas and if there is no
default scheme in a particular community, it cannot be imposed from a top down position.  This can result in areas of need not having access to a CT scheme while more affluent communities, with more access to volunteers with nice cars, have thriving schemes.
default&#xa0;
default5.4.
default 
defaultMan
defaulty potential passengers cannot afford longer journeys in a CT vehicle, even though they are cheaper than commercial alternatives.  Many people in 
defaultNorfolk
default live 20 miles or more from a major hospital, which would result in a round trip costing around £18.  Ou
defaultt of county trips to specialist hospitals such as 
defaultPapworth
default could cost around £90 (this might be reduced if a subsidy is available but the passenger would still have to pay £45).
default&#xa0;
default5.5.
default 
defaultOnly CTOs running buses with Section 22 licences are eligible to accept 
defaultconcessionary travel passes.  This limits their ability to offer affordable transport to some of the most disadvantaged groups of people in the community and means that some operators have extra
default administration from running two
default different types of licence.
default&#xa0;
default5.6.
default 
defaultCTOs experienced a significant drop in demand for services purchased by adult social services department as a result in cuts to local government funding affecting day centres.  Many of these have closed with the result that some 
defaultisolated individuals have n
defaultowhere to go and no opportunity to use the transport that is available to them.  CTOs had a sudden drop in income that has affected their ability to run sustainable services.
default  
defaultThe introduction of personalised budgets has also had an impact on CTOs as previ
defaultous contracts to provide transport for groups of people from Social Services departments have ended and there is no automatic inclusion of transport costs when individuals plan and agree their budgets.  Some people are making the decision to buy their tran
defaultsport from a range of sources.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default6.1.
default 
defaultThere are a number of barriers faced by Community Transport Operators in 
defaultNorfolk
default.  The main ones are:
default&#xa0;
default6.1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe commissioning agenda – CTOs are seeking full cost recovery from 
defaultcontracts so that other areas of income are not cross-subsidising local authority contracts.  They are competing against commercial providers who are putting in very low bids that are acting as a loss leader.  Sometimes this results in these organisations 
defaulthaving to withdraw from contracts before completion.  Norfolk County Council is seeking to cut their costs and
default many standard contracts are awarded
default only on the basis of price rather than value for money.  The Public Services (Social Value) Act is having lim
defaultited impact in changing this culture although a recent transport contract did include social criteria.  CTOs will not bid for contracts if they don’t make 
defaultan operating surplus
default from them
default.  
defaultThe majority of c
defaultontracts issued by NCC tend to be short term (1 yea
defaultr) that do not enable contract holders to develop long term plans
default&#xa0;
default6.1.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLack of engagement by health providers in CT.  GP surgeries and hospitals 
defaulta
defaultr
defaulte the main organisational beneficiaries of community transport but make no financial contribution to the services
default.  CTOs could help to reduce costs of non emergency medical transport to the ambulance service, freeing resources to concentrate on emergency services.
default  This would also achieve other cost savings for health providers.
default&#xa0;
default6.1.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRecruiting volunteers – this is a con
defaultstant concern for all types of CTO.  As described above, the volunteer profile is aging and 
defaultsome schemes are not able to recruit younger volunteers.
default  
defaultThere is a lack of trustee volunteers coming forward to take over from aging ones 
defaulton
default CT
defaultO
default 
defaultboards
default.
default  
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaulttravel expenses
default rate for volunteers is set at 45p for 
defaultup to
default10,000 miles
